<dl id="n12004j"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n12" href="#n12004j">N12 (VI.B.14)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n12all.htm#n12004j"> 4(j)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> dwarfs (cousins) / corrigans</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">Ce ne sont pas elles qui ont construit tous les dolmens; beaucoup aussi sont l&apos;&oelig;uvre des nains, petits &ecirc;tres noirs, velus, aux yeux moqueurs et dont la taille ne d&eacute;passe pas vingt centim&egrave;tres. <font color="green">[&hellip;]</font> On leur a donn&eacute; dans nos r&eacute;gions des noms vari&eacute;s; les plus ordinaires sont ceux de korrigans, follets, crions, poulpiquets, fadets, gorics, boudighets et corrandouns. <br><font color="green">[They did not build all the dolmens, many were also the work of <mark>dwarves</mark>, small, black, hairy creatures with mocking eyes and no taller than twenty centimetres. [&hellip;]</font> In our regions, they have been given various names; the most common are <i><mark>korrigans</mark>, follets, crions, poulpiquets, fadets, gorics, boudighets</i>, and <i>corrandouns</i>.] <small> l'Abb&eacute; A. Millon, <a name="AMPB" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#AMPB"><cite title="source">Pauvres Pierres! Les Megalithes Bretons devant la science</cite></a> (n.d) 11</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Note: French, <i>bossu</i>: hunchback. </mm> </dd></dl>
